Comment:
Classical case, of adaptation butchering the source material.


SPOILERS



The parts of the book that leave the strongest impression on people are lost completly.
Do we see the monster struggling with searching a meaning for his lone life, abandoned by his creator, hated by everyone?
No we get a dumb aggressive meatsack.
Do we feel Frankenstein's pain and doubts? The pain he feels over the loss of the love of his life by the hands of his creation? and the possiblity that he could create a race of savages that could exterminate humanity?
No.
We just get a wild manbeast who is dealt with quickly and without any major problem.
Do we get the feeling that frankenstein is in the search of something new, not meant to known to men, and the horror when he realises it?
No...
Instead we get, a misguided crusader pursuing him. (That makes all of the above impossible. If he is in the search of such thing, a detective - or any other person for the matter - would have no clue what he is doing. What is even worse, that the only harm he is in the way, is the aggression of the said cop.)

SO PLEASE NO MORE ADAPTATIONS!

Title: Victor Frankenstein | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
This looks good and all but I want to see a faithful adaptation of the original Mary Shelley's Frankenstein.

Nowadays, the "Monster" is always this evil unintelligent creature who only destroys. In the original novel, the monster was a sentient creature who felt the world was beautiful and wondered why he was the only "hideous" creature. He really wanted to live with other people and even taught himself to speak and read. He only ever ate berries and nuts. He always tried to make friends with people but they would always fear him and hunt him so in the end he gave up hope and decided to be the "monster" that the people thought he was. Maybe someday in the future someone will decide to go back to the roots of Frankenstein and his monster. Anyways cool trailer!

Comment:
i think it's a little depressing that few modern works have actually stayed true to the idea of the original Shelly novel - that the Creature isn't some kind of mindless monster or zombie, but an intelligent humanoid whose fatal flaw is his appearance.

the book in fact makes a very convincing case for Victor Frankenstein, not the Creature, being the antagonist through his denial to grant the Creature his only wish - a female counterpart (and, by proxy, a normal life similar to any other human's).

there's no need to dilute and defile the depth of the original narrative with all this action and spectacle. kind of disappointed that this is the direction that the director chose to take...

Title: Victor Frankenstein | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
It looks like it's trying to be to the Frankenstein stories what Guy Ritchie and Robert Downey Jr. were to the Sherlock Holmes stories. And it looks like it's trying too hard.

Also, I've never read the original novel or seen any Frankenstein movie (I did buy the one with Kenneth Brannaghand Robert Deniro from the $5 movie bin last night though if that counts but haven't watched it yet) so correct me if I'm wrong, but... were fans of the original work really clamoring to see the bromance between Igor and Victor expanded upon? And was the original work this light hearted and filled with funny one-liners? Again, haven't read the novel but I highly doubt it was.

I like both the main actors in this movie, but the entire trailer just makes the movie seem not only like a lazy cash grab, but a disservice to a great novel that has inspired the imagination of millions. Now I hope I'm wrong, because I have been wrong before (Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs, 21 Jump Street, Kung Fu Panda) but I've also been right before (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles(2014), Fant4stic). We'll see.
